","1280–Female":"1280–Deceased","1330":"1330","1284":"1284","1280":"1280","1315":"1315","1312":"1312","about 1317":"about 1317","1310":"1310","about 1315":"about 1315","1320":"1320","1353":"1353","about 1312":"about 1312","about 1310":"about 1310","about 1320":"about 1320","1317":"1317","Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, España":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain","Toledo, Nueva Castilla, España":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain","Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Espanha":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain","España":"Spain","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Garcia","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jesus, Carlos, Luis, Francisco, Pedro, Miguel, Jorge, Mario, Raul, Roberto, Ramon, Rafael.  Portuguese Wenceslao, Joao, Paulo, Catarina, Albeiro, Ligia, Godofredo, Lidio, Wenseslao, Adao, Afonso.","Spanish (<b>García</b>) and Portuguese: from a medieval personal name of uncertain origin. It is normally found in medieval records in the Latin form <i>Garsea</i>, and may well be of pre-Roman origin, perhaps akin to Basque <i>(h)artz</i> ‘bear’. This is the most common surname in Spain and also one of the most common surnames elsewhere in Spanish-speaking world. In the US, where it is also found among Native Americans (mainly Pueblos in NM), it is the sixth most frequent surname. Compare   De Garcia  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Grassia","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Amedeo, Maurizio, Pasquale, Rocco, Salvatore.","Italian: from a metathesized form of the personal name<i>Garsia</i>, from Spanish <i>García</i> (see   Garcia  )."]},{"name":"Arcia","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Alberto, Francisco, Arturo, Dagoberto, Enrique, Jose, Ramiro, Adalberto, Aleida, Alejandro, Alfredo, Amalia.","Hispanic: probably an altered form of Spanish <b>García</b> (see   Garcia  )."]},{"name":"Garcie","meanings":["Altered form, under the French influence in LA, of Spanish <b>García</b> (see   Garcia  ). This form of the surname of Spanish origin is also found in southern France.","Spanish (Ávila): variant of <b>García</b> (see   Garcia  )."]},{"name":"Garcilazo","meanings":["Hispanic (mainly Mexico and Argentina): altered form of Spanish (Valencia) <b>Garcilaso</b>, a compound of the personal name <i>Garci</i> (a short form of <i>García</i>, see   Garcia  ) and the nickname <i>laso</i> ‘weak, exhausted’."]},{"name":"Gacia","meanings":["Hispanic: altered form of Spanish <b>García</b> (see   Garcia  )."]},{"name":"Garsia","meanings":["Hispanic: altered form of   Garcia  ."]},{"name":"Gracia","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Juan, Manuel, Francisco, Jesus, Luis, Guadalupe, Mario, Pedro, Javier, Jorge.","Spanish; Catalan (<b>Gràcia</b>): from a short form of the Christian religious epithet <i>de la Gracia</i>, meaning ‘of mercy’ and forming part of the Marian name <i>Maria de la Gracia</i> ‘(Holy) Mary of Grace’, from Spanish <i>gracia</i>, Catalan <i>gràcia</i> ‘grace, mercy’.","In some cases possibly also an altered form of Spanish <b>García</b> (see   Garcia  )."]},{"name":"De Garcia","meanings":["Spanish and Galician (<b>De García</b>); Portuguese: patronymic from Spanish and Galician <b>García</b> and Portuguese   Garcia  , with the preposition <i>de</i> ‘of’."]},{"name":"Garces","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jorge, Carlos, Juan, Jose, Manuel, Cesar, Rafael, Luis, Fernando, Gustavo, Javier, Mario.  Portuguese Albeiro, Paulo.","Spanish; Catalan (<b>Garcés</b>); Portuguese (<b>Garcês</b>): patronymic from the personal name <i>García</i> (see   Garcia  )."]},{"name":"Garzia","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Mario, Alfredo, Ernestina, Fernando, Juan, Pedro, Ricardo.  Italian Angelo, Antonio, Ciro, Corrado.","Italianized form of Spanish   Garcia  ."]}]},{"name":"Maria","type":"FIRST","meanings":["A name derived from Mapia, one of the Greek forms of Miriam. Maria is found as a male name as well as a female name. Viscount Montague, of Cowdray, Sussex, who succeeded to the title as second viscount, was christened Anthony Maria Browne. In Camden's Remains (p. 44), referred to in Delicie Literarise, occurs Thomas Maria Wingfield; and there was also a Sir Edward Maria Wingfield. The name appears to have been adopted in the latter family from Mary, daughter of Henry VIII. Compare Notes and Queries 5th S. ii. 73, 316, 478. Marie is frequently found as a male name in France and in other parts of the Continent."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Maria Garcia was born in 1280, in Spain. She had at least 2 sons and 3 daughters with Diego Garcia de Toledo I. She died in her hometown."},"et":{"1280–":"1280–Surnud","1284–1330":"1284–1330","1310–1353":"1310–1353","1312–Female":"1312–Surnud","1315–Male":"1315–Surnud","1317–Female":"1317–Surnud","1320–Female":"1320–Surnud","1280–Female":"1280–Surnud","1330":"1330","1284":"1284","1280":"1280","1315":"1315","1312":"1312","about 1317":"umbes 1317","1310":"1310","about 1315":"umbes 1315","1320":"1320","1353":"1353","about 1312":"umbes 1312","about 1310":"umbes 1310","about 1320":"umbes 1320","1317":"1317","Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, España":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Hispaania","Toledo, Nueva Castilla, España":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Hispaania","Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Espanha":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Hispaania","España":"Hispaania"},"fi":{"1280–":"1280–Kuollut","1284–1330":"1284–1330","1310–1353":"1310–1353","1312–Female":"1312–Kuollut","1315–Male":"1315–Kuollut","1317–Female":"1317–Kuollut","1320–Female":"1320–Kuollut","1280–Female":"1280–Kuollut","1330":"1330","1284":"1284","1280":"1280","1315":"1315","1312":"1312","about 1317":"noin 1317","1310":"1310","about 1315":"noin 1315","1320":"1320","1353":"1353","about 1312":"noin 1312","about 1310":"noin 1310","about 1320":"noin 1320","1317":"1317","Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, España":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Es